This course provides an overview of the definitions, concepts, and theories of governance and explores the emergence of new governance arrangements in relation to the traditional public administration (TPA) and New Public Management (NPM) in the operation of public sectors around the world. The course focuses on the implications of governance on public policy-making and service delivery and includes case discussions of the issues and challenges of various instruments of public action for effectiveness and democratic accountability.Objectives/eesmärkid:  This is a course about public governance that introduces students to governance in public administration and public policy. In this course, students learn about the new approaches to solving public problems in the rapidly changing context of managing public affairs where the achievement of public purposes is increasingly dependent on the interactions between the state, market, and civil society actors in self-organizing inter-organizational governance arenas.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Upon completion of this course, the students will be able to: 1) comprehend the evolution of the modes of public action in the operation of public sectors that have led to the emergence of new public governance; 2) be able to explain the meanings of the major concepts of governance; 3) identify and assess the principles, practices, and instruments of public action in the age of governance; 4) be able to critically analyze and evaluate the impact of various forms of governance on policy effectiveness and democracy; 5) master the basic skills of desiging, writing, and presenting a comparative analysis on the governance of a chosen issue.
